<CaseStudy
  title="Charac — NHS-Integrated Pharmacy Analytics"
  description="Turned Charac's operational data into reporting pharmacy teams and the growth side could actually use — Power BI over prescriptions, deliveries and consultations; GA4 event tracking on the patient app."
  role="Data Analyst · Charac — pharmacy-tech platform"
  period="Sep 2025 – Present"
  stack={['Power BI', 'DAX', 'GA4', 'BigQuery', 'SQL', 'ETL/ELT', 'NHS IG']}
  outcome="Live reporting layer across Greater London pharmacy network — operational KPIs for pharmacy owners, acquisition + retention signals for growth."
  liveUrl="https://charac.co.uk"
>

  <h2>The platform</h2>
  <p>
    Charac gives community pharmacies one system for prescriptions, deliveries,
    consultations and patient comms, with NHS Login and EPS built in.
    I worked on the data side — turning the platform's operational data into
    reporting pharmacy teams and the growth side could actually use.
  </p>

  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>
    A pharmacist is a clinician, not an analyst. They needed to see how their
    pharmacy was performing without a data team sitting behind them. On growth,
    the harder problem is awareness — most patients don't know which services
    their pharmacy offers, so the acquisition signals that matter most are
    top-of-funnel discovery events, not just conversions.
  </p>

  <h2>The constraint</h2>
  <div class="callout">
    <p>
      <strong>NHS IG:</strong> Charac operates as a data processor under NHS
      Information Governance rules — pharmacies own their data. Every report
      worked from aggregated, pseudonymised data; nothing patient-identifiable
      touched the BI layer. This constraint shaped every modelling decision.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>What I did</h2>

  <h3>Power BI reporting</h3>
  <p>
    Built dashboards over prescription, delivery and consultation data.
    Logic-heavy SQL and ETL upstream keeps the DAX layer clean:
    Prescription Hub (volume, fulfilment SLA), Delivery Tracker (on-time rate,
    exceptions), Consultation Demand (booking trends, capacity vs. demand).
    The growth team got a separate view — acquisition funnel, patient retention
    cohorts, and channel attribution from GA4.
  </p>

  <h3>GA4 event tracking</h3>
  <p>
    Defined and implemented a clean event taxonomy on the patient app to follow
    the journey and find drop-off: prescription requests, delivery tracking opens,
    consultation bookings. Connected GA4 export to the Power BI acquisition
    model via BigQuery for end-to-end attribution from channel to first
    prescription fulfilled.
  </p>

  <h3>SQL / ETL</h3>
  <p>
    Heavy logic lives upstream. Pre-aggregated SQL views keep dashboard queries
    fast; an NHS calendar dimension handles bank-holiday prescription-volume
    anomalies that would otherwise surface as false SLA flags.
  </p>

  <h2>Reach</h2>
  <div class="stat-row">
    <div class="stat-box">
      <span class="stat-num">Live</span>
      <span class="stat-lbl">Greater London (owner portal + patient app)</span>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-box">
      <span class="stat-num">100+</span>
      <span class="stat-lbl">pharmacies across the UK on the platform</span>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-box">
      <span class="stat-num">80+</span>
      <span class="stat-lbl">NHS community pharmacies in the London area</span>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-box">
      <span class="stat-num">NHS IG</span>
      <span class="stat-lbl">compliant throughout</span>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--text-lo); margin-top: 12px;">
    Prescription, patient and performance figures stay confidential under data-processor obligations.
  </p>

  <h2>What I'd change</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Push complexity upstream.</strong> A few complex DAX measures caused
    slow loads on the pharmacy-owner view before I rewrote them as pre-aggregated
    SQL views. Default position: complexity lives in SQL, not DAX.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Self-serve adoption needs onboarding.</strong> Dashboards were adopted
    well by the operations team but pharmacy owners needed more than expected.
    Next version would embed contextual tooltips directly in the Power BI views
    and include a short walkthrough. Analytics only creates value if the people
    it's built for actually use it.
  </p>

</CaseStudy>
